tip.text:
This sweet and pokey independent bookshop on Lower Clapton Road proves that wonderful things often come in small packages. Youâ€™ll find an extensive selection upstairs, ranging from contemporary fiction to gorgeous coffee table books - while the downstairs room, complete with couch, offers vintage Penguin books, first editions and vinyl to boot.

Pages of Hackney also stage a number of events: from book readings to photography exhibitions, and are proud to have hosted talks from the likes of China Mielville and Melissa Benn in the past. Get down and help keep printed word alive!

This gem of a cafe is a welcome addition to Hackney serving up delicious coffee blends in a minimal and airy space adorned with retro stylings. It's just the kind of cafe you'd expect to find in such ends: calm, white walls, full of people doing things on their laptops that are innumerably more important than whatever you are doing on yours.

They pride themselves on their coffee here, so kick things off with a cup of joe, while you decide whether their brunch menu is tempting enough to hang around for. Sourdough bread, slow-roast beans, fried mushrooms and prosciutto topped with poached eggs sure worked on us.

Take yourself to the quaint village that is Clapton, give your moustache a good twirl and then squeeze your bum into a seat in this wee crÃªperie - or if the weather is nice come find us amongst the lavender outback. Now listen carefully dearies; the menu is broken up into crÃªpes and galettes. Galettes are made with buckwheat flour, water and salt - nothing else, which makes them crunchy and a little nutty to taste. They are then topped with all manner of proper French goodies, from homemade ratatouille and blue cheese sauce to Bayonne ham with sautÃ©ed potatoes and Reblochon (one of the smelliest of the cheeses).

The list of crepes is - we are pleased to say - almost as long as the savouries. Standouts are flambÃ©ed pear, chocolate sauce and vanilla ice cream or if you're feeling a little fancy try the sugar, fresh orange and lemon juice with a generous swig of Grand Marnier. Ooft yes please Mr French guy!

Safâ€™s been keeping the people of lower Clapton fly for nigh on 25 years now so you can bet heâ€™s seen the neighbourhood change a whole lot. Step into his time capsule of a barbershop and find yourself in the calm eye of the storm - get a trim, have a friendly chat with this fine Turkish gentleman and appreciate the beauty of longevity. Keep your eyes peeled for the snap of Saf and Trevor McDonald on the wall; pretty solid proof that the manâ€™s handy with clippers and scissors if you ask us.

P. Franco is a bit of an institution on the low intervention wine scene - almost single handedly making 'natural' the coolest wine for Londoners to drink. By day it's a mighty friendly shop stocking unpretentious liquids - of varying price range. (France and Italy dominate the wine offerings but you can still expect a hefty selection of bottles here, from the USA to Australia.)

By night (four a week) it becomes one of the most intimate eating experiences about. Where guest chefs work their magic over two induction hobs and serve up all sorts of goodies to a large communal table. Though cooking styles change depending on who's in the kitchen, you can always expect high calibre grub from these guys - paired with intriguing natural wine selects. Our fave bit? The way beginners and wine geeks are welcomed with equally smiley faces.

Kitchen times:
Thurs: 6-9
Fri-Sat: 6-10
Sun: 2-9

It's always a good sign when a venue has a really small menu. Yard Sale Pizza not only only do pizza but also have a small menu. Grab one of these scrummy pizzas to eat in or takeaway. We love the butternut squash, goats cheese, rocket and honey drizzle (no mozzarella). For the real meat lovers the pepperoni, fennel sausage, spicy beef, black olives, mixed peppers and mushrooms never goes amiss. It's not all dough though with a selection of salads and some banging beers.

Any mention of Clapton and bucket-loads of cool ensue, and that's exactly the case with Biddle Bros. Situated on the frontline of London gentrification behind the spot's original shop front - this joint is a breath of fresh air, despite the many questionable mustaches it's packed with. Expect jazz in the early evening, dj's spinning ambient bangers later on and spectacularly reasonable prices, not to mention you'll find the likes of Staropramen, and Boddingtons on tap.

As soon as you enter the room here youâ€™ll know you've found the right conditions to soothe the nut. In a beautiful circular church, lit by candles and pink and purple hues, this is a sound gong bath. What would your school friends say if they could see you now? They'd be very impressed, we'd wager. Youâ€™ll lie on a mat with your head towards the gongs, covered by rugs and feeling all snug, ready to let the mind drift to wherever it fancies.

The gongs and Tibetan singing bowls create deep and immersive waves of sound that are richly atmospheric - sometimes sparse, sometimes layered, and occasionally apocalyptic but not in a scary way. It's a pretty unique experience: you might be transported off to some distant galaxy, you might keep thinking about what youâ€™re going to eat afterwards. But one thing is for sure - it is relaxing.

The Psychedelic Society put on plenty of similar events to this - from dancing in the dark to song circles, inner visions and a host of talks. The use of psychedelics is not encouraged, though were you to come to this on acid or something you would probably have a blast. Check their website for upcoming events.

Itâ€™s a shame you canâ€™t drink in this craft haven, but you can certainly do some stocking up for the nuclear apocalypse. Maybe you know what a growler is, maybe you donâ€™t - short story shorter itâ€™s a big â€˜ol vessel (just shy of 2l) to carry beer in. Well, theyâ€™ve got plenty growlers here and you can fill it up with your choice of 8 brews on tap. Counter pressure means beers stay fresh for 6 weeks!

The walls are absolutely packed with craft bottles, be they local or global, so donâ€™t try telling us you couldnâ€™t find anything you liked here. Locally produced gin, rum and vodka have all managed to find themselves stocked here. Much booze to be had.

This taqueria has all the spice of a real roadside joint without any of the bowel anxiety. Work your way through a veggie jackfruit taco, topped with crunchy sweet potato; or a taco packed with slow-cooked lamb topped with coriander and onions; and a steak quesadilla perhaps? It's important you know it wouldn't be weird to order one of every taco. No shame; be free, young warrior.

The drinks are just as cray as the colourful decor. Get off on lime, watermelon or cucumber margaritas (with your choice of tequila or mezcal) or try your hand at a 'Michelada', which is basically a beer-based Bloody Mary. Curious aren't you pussy cat?

Ps: It's Â£2 tacos on Tuesdays. Hells yeah.

Thereâ€™s a definite beauty in simple pleasures. Kicking back and listening to wax spin while you sip on a coffee has got to be one of those: swing by here and listen to records in a supremely chilled setting, with coffee from the delightful roasters at All Press and fresh juices on the menu to boot. Drinks might get a little bit stiffer once the sun goes down but you wonâ€™t find us complaining about that.

Have All Saints started doing cocktail bars? The Bonneville definitely has that vibe, with the shabby walls, ram skulls on the wall, and old school lighting. That curved stained glass ceiling up the back is freakin' gorgeous though, and we have to admit, the whole shabby Parisian feel of the place is a winner...particularly the fog they produce with dry ice.

Old school cocktails are on the menu too, like Mint Juleps, and the menu keeps things French with dishes like Ratatouille. The grub's not bad, but it's the feel of the joint that we love.

The Hackney area may not be short on gorgeous buns, but here's some more for the squeezing. Warm, fresh and sticky, they're an absolute delight thanks to the two lads at this 'micro' bakery. Open seven days a week, Charles Good Food is all about the simple, honest baking life, without any additives. It dishes out freshly baked sandwiches; sourdoughs; lemon and poppy seed, cinnamon, cardamom and custard buns and more. Choco fans like us can nab some home-made chocolate truffles with tonka bean, white chocolate, dark chocolate and orange to take away too.

There's nowhere to sit, so grab your goodies and sling your hook.

It's a well known fact that judging a cafe around this area is partly to do with the quality and value of the food but mainly down to its aesthetic value. Insta is important and you really ought not forget that. Cafe Miami, situated in the beautiful, rather incongruous listed Strand Building brings a nice dose of Art Deco to Clapton, with its pastel hues, retro furnishings and Americana specialities.

The main talking point is probably the interior - plenty of phones come out at this place - and, to be honest, the food is nothing above your usual brunch fare; albeit with some Miami-inspired decadence. Waffle burgers with chorizo, avocado and fried egg; fish finger tacos; and hot honey smoked salmon with ricotta on focaccia all promise plenty of richness and come in around the Â£9 mark.

The Miyazaki influence is strong here: from the ornate, faded wallpaper to the small toy train perpetually travelling on its lonely loop around the cosy little restaurant, My Neighbours The Dumplings is dripping with the same melancholic charm that the Japanese auteur is known for - you half expect Totoro to show up and whisk you away on a fantastical adventure.

But, alas, the only adventure youâ€™ll be going on at MNTD is of the culinary kind. With a menu committed to the dumpling, paying no mind to geographical differences, you can expect all kinds of innovative pan-Asian dishes that are either 1) dumplings, or 2) designed to compliment dumplings (sometimes we think this is what we were designed for). Made fresh everyday, the parcels themselves are delicate and bursting with flavour, with flairs of innovation wherever you look, while punchy side salads and a sake-focused drinks list offer excellent palate cleansers/time fillers between portions.

That vegan cafe in Bethnal Green everyone is raving about. You've heard of it. We're sure you have. It's 100% vegan, community run and not for profit. Get your vegan samosas, sausage rolls, cakes and milkshakes, or go for a posh coffee.

You can also buy produce to take away, including vegan cheeses, faux meats, tofu, tempeh, Club Mate & Fritz Kola (German drinks), as well as politically-charged vegan cookbooks. Because you never know when you might need one. Hell, you could probably use one right now.

It's like Britain and Japan got into a fight, made up, then opened up a cafe together. Pacific Social Club describes itself as a drop-out centre and wannabe Izakaya. What does that mean for you? Great coffee and cakes to the soundtrack of vintage vinyls by day, but in the evenings from Thursday to Saturday you have the mighty Japanese Sho Foo Doh kitchen takeover.

We don't know how they came up with this intercontinental mix, but we wish there were more like it.

This Japanese joint on a Clapton back street is simplicity personified (restaurantified?). Take a seat at the sunken sharing tables (shoes off, of course) or a stool by the window and flick through the short menu. It's sushi, sashimi and nigiri on one section; skewers and hot delicacies on another; and a page at the back for nibbles and puddings. The limited options and simple descriptions give you time to really think about what you'd like to feast on - although our answer is usually 'everything'.

The softshell crab sushi is a real winner; as is the tuna sashimi which comes as three thick slabs of succulent pink fish. As for the hots, we'd tip the grilled mackerel skewers with a tangy sweet vinegar - one of the nicest mouthfuls of fish we'd had in a while. Everything feels straight forward and well considered, and sipping a crisp Japanese lager between each course is a truly pleasurable experience.

All your grocery needs and then some, Palm 2 (we donâ€™t know of a Palm 1) is much, much more than your local supermarket. Youâ€™ll find plenty of local produce on these shelves, including Beavertown beers and Union coffee, while thereâ€™s heaps to snack on from the deli section too. Does your corner shop do a Sunday roast? Didnâ€™t think so, but this one does! Tables out front are perfect for soaking up a spot of sun and shooting the shit with your neighbours, while the cheeky coffee window means you can grab a quick one on the go.

This underground cubby hole provides excellent seasonal cocktails, a small menu of tasty bites and some of the best quality sound this side of the Brandenburg Gate. Propping up the bar here reminds us of being in the kitchen at a house party - a particularly stylish one. It may be a squeeze, but you get the feeling you'll miss something truly great if you leave. It wouldn't be unusual to share a knowing smile with the DJ over some crisp electronic beats; or swap a joke with the bar staff while they cooly whip you up a blend of unknown spirits with genuinely inventive seasonal touches. This is a cocktail emporium of the most laid-back variety; a good time bar with exceedingly good taste.
